<section><div class="sec-inner">
<h2 class="h2">Frequently asked questions</h2>
<ul class="faq-list">
  <li class="faq-item">
    <div class="faq-q">Is Fathom really free for individual users?</div>
    <div class="faq-a">Yes. Fathom's individual free tier is genuinely usable, not a bait-and-switch. It records, transcribes, and summarizes unlimited meetings on Zoom, Google Meet, and Microsoft Teams at no cost. The paid tier ($30/seat/month) adds team-sharing features, custom summary templates, and CRM integrations.</div>
  </li>
  <li class="faq-item">
    <div class="faq-q">What is the best AI meeting summary tool for small businesses?</div>
    <div class="faq-a">Fathom is the top pick for most small businesses in 2026. The free plan covers solo operators and small teams completely. If you need CRM sync or team-wide sharing, the paid plan at $30/seat is the most cost-effective option compared to Gong ($130+/seat) or Chorus. Otter.ai is a solid second choice if transcript search matters more than summary quality.</div>
  </li>
  <li class="faq-item">
    <div class="faq-q">How does Gong compare to Otter.ai for sales teams?</div>
    <div class="faq-a">Gong is built specifically for sales call intelligence: deal risk signals, coaching scorecards, and deep CRM writeback. Otter.ai is a general-purpose transcription and summary tool with lighter sales-specific features. For teams with 10 or more active salespeople and a structured sales process, Gong's pipeline analytics justify the higher price ($130-$160/seat). For teams under 10 or without a formal coaching program, Otter or Fathom at a fraction of the cost will do the job.</div>
  </li>
  <li class="faq-item">
    <div class="faq-q">Can AI meeting summary tools integrate with Salesforce and HubSpot?</div>
    <div class="faq-a">Yes, but integration depth varies. Gong and Chorus offer the deepest CRM integrations, writing call summaries, action items, and deal stage changes directly into Salesforce or HubSpot records. Fathom syncs meeting notes and action items to both CRMs on its paid plan. Otter and Fireflies offer lighter integrations (notes pushed as activity records). DIY Claude requires a manual copy-paste workflow unless you build an automation via Zapier or Make.</div>
  </li>
  <li class="faq-item">
    <div class="faq-q">What is the cheapest AI meeting notetaker that actually works?</div>
    <div class="faq-a">Fathom's free plan is the cheapest option that produces quality output. For teams, Fireflies.ai starts at $10/seat/month with solid multi-platform support. The absolute lowest-cost approach is DIY: record with Zoom's built-in recorder, transcribe with Whisper (open source, free), and summarize with a Claude API call. Total cost for a small team using this approach can be under $30/month total.</div>
  </li>
  <li class="faq-item">
    <div class="faq-q">Does Read.ai work with Microsoft Teams and Zoom?</div>
    <div class="faq-a">Yes. Read.ai supports Zoom, Microsoft Teams, and Google Meet. It joins meetings as a bot, records, transcribes, and produces a summary with its signature engagement analytics (attention scores, talk-time ratios, sentiment signals). The engagement analytics layer is Read.ai's main differentiator from Fathom and Otter, which focus on transcript quality and summary structure rather than participant behavior.</div>
  </li>
  <li class="faq-item">
    <div class="faq-q">What AI meeting summary tool works without a meeting bot joining the call?</div>
    <div class="faq-a">Most dedicated tools (Fathom, Otter, Fireflies, Read.ai) join as a bot, which can feel intrusive in some contexts. Fathom has a local desktop app mode that records without sending a bot into the meeting. The bot-free approach with full control: use your platform's native recording, run the audio file through Whisper for transcription, then send the transcript to Claude with a structured prompt. This produces summaries with no bot attendee, no vendor data sharing, and complete prompt control.</div>
  </li>
</ul>
